name: Ivory Bracelet
hint: Bracelets were worn by both men and women, rich and poor. They could be made of bone, ivory, metal, or polished stone.

name: Eye (Wadjet) Amulet
hint: A powerful symbol of protection, the eye was sometimes a symbol of the goddess Wadjet; but it could also represent the "Eye of Horus" or the "Eye of Ra."

name: Model of Bread-Making Scene
hint: Bread was a staple of the ancient Egyptian diet, and grain for making bread was one common form of payment for work.

name: Jar
hint: Beer, wine, honey, and olive oil were stored in jars and offered to the dead. This jar represents beer, called henket.

name: Jackal
hint: In Egypt, the death god Anubis was represented by a jackal head; but not every jackal was Anubis. The jackal on this jar does represent the god seated on a shrine.

name: Model Funerary Boat with Crew
hint: Ancient Egyptians visualized death as a boat journey across the Nile. The funerary boat transported the soul from this life to the afterlife. So models of funerary boats were often included in tombs.

name: Feathers (On a Scarab)
hint: On this scarab, the feathers represent Ma’at, the goddess of truth, justice, and order. Ancient Egyptians feared chaos above all else, so much was done to make Ma’at happy!

name: Model Beef Haunch
hint: Cows were an important part of the ancient Egyptian agricultural system, providing labor, meat, and milk products.
